, exploring, and understanding fictional, imaginary, and invented languagesBrings together many of the key creators, designers and researchers of imagined languages in literature, TV and cinemaFeatures the languages of Tolkien’s Middle Earth, Star Trek, Avatar, Game of Thrones, Dune, and SpEEC, Lapin, Láadan, Marain, Speedtalk, Heptapod B, and many others including a language invented exclusively for this bookServes as both a handbook and guide to the creation, design principles, exploration, analysis and experience of reading fictional languagesReading Fictional Languages brings together scholars, creators, designers and speakers of fictional languages from across the world in a unique book that explores the imagined languages of fantasy, science fiction, dystopia and alternate realities. It explores the role of invented languages in world-building, characterisation, and the feeling of authentic immersion in the forms of thought of aliens, animals, machines, and the people who inhabit alternative worlds from our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aImaginary languages in literature. 0aScience fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aScience fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Science Fiction & Fantasy.2bisacsh1 aAndrade, Victor Fernandes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeinhoff, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobeck, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampi, Nicolás Matías, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutierrez, Anthony, ec